    <h1 class="text-2xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-slate-900 sm:text-3xl mb-4">Integrity in Research and Scholarship Policy</h1>
    <div class="prose prose-slate max-w-none">
      <p><strong>Policy Title:</strong> Integrity in Research and Scholarship Policy (IRSP)</p>
      <p><strong>Policy Number:</strong> RS-PO-4E</p>
      <p><strong>Date Created:</strong> 15-02-2023</p>
      <p><strong>Responsible:</strong> Vice President Research and Excellence</p>
      <p><strong>Approved by:</strong> Board of Trustees</p>
      <h2>Purpose</h2>
      <p>The purpose of this policy is to provide guidelines, related to the integrity in research and scholarship, to the CUD community who are involved in research and scholarly activities.</p>
      <h2>Scope</h2>
      <p>This policy applies to all the CUD community who are involved in scholarly activities which includes research, theory development, teaching and learning, and the production, performance, presentation or publication of scholarly papers, works of art, or other forms of expression.</p>
      <h2>Policy Statement</h2>
      <p>The document is based on the understanding that scholarly activity includes research, theory development, teaching and learning, and the production, performance, presentation or publication of scholarly papers, works of art, or other forms of expression. It assumes the development and maintenance of a culture of equity at CUD, a culture where the standard operating procedures are rooted in principles of fairness and justice. It does not replace other means of determining fairness, such as the office of the Ombudsperson, the Human Right Office, nor procedures such as student appeals, employee grievances, or any existing collective agreements. Instead, this Policy complements these and other CUD policies and procedures, including those governing the ethics of research with human subjects, animals, biohazards, radioactive substances, occupational health and safety, and student conduct.</p>
      <p>The general public has a legitimate interest in the maintenance of standards of scholarly conduct at an Academic Institution. Therefore, CUD is responsible for maintaining such standards in a way that is open to scrutiny. CUD is responsible for promoting a clear understanding of the issues involved in maintaining the highest standards in research, teaching, learning and other aspects of scholarship. CUD is also responsible for providing an environment that encourages recognition of ethical standards. CUD is responsible to respond appropriately for the allegations of misconduct involving its administrators, personnel or students. Finally, the University is accountable for assessing and reviewing policies and practices to ensure that the highest ethical standards are maintained over time. Therefore, CUD faculty members, administrators, employees and students are directly responsible for ensuring the standards listed in this document.</p>
      <h3>Definitions</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Academic Dishonesty</strong> is defined as but not limited to: fabrication or falsification of research results, plagiarism, forgery of documents, failure to appropriately recognize the substantive contributions of others, use of unpublished works without permission, and more.</li>
        <li><strong>Misuse of Research Funds</strong> is defined as but not limited to: failure to use research funds in strict accordance with the terms and conditions of grants and contracts, failure to follow University’s financial directives, failing to disclose a financial or personal interest in any transaction chargeable to a research grant or contract, and more.</li>
        <li><strong>Conflict of Interest</strong> is defined as but not limited to: failure to disclose existing, potential or apparent personal, financial or business interests of the researcher, the researcher’s associates or the researcher’s family in relationship to research grants and contract, failure to comply with the University policy on conflict of interest, and more.</li>
      </ul>
